node.text:
this pandemic has really done a number on my mental health (i’m sure many of you can relate). i’m surviving, but i don’t really feel like i’m thriving. it’s really important for me to continuously find ways to help boost my general energy and mood as it can help to keep me out of dark headspaces. there really are so many things you can do to increase your serotonin levels. i find myself creating checklists of what i can personally do daily. it usually helps on most days, but on the days it doesn’t, i just succumb to my heavier moods. i feel the feelings and ride out the day (or days).
it’s also important to note that in a lot of cases simple things like a walk or “mood foods” is not enough to help stabilize a mood. so, however, you get your serotonin (naturally or store-bought) is OKAY 🖤 we’re just human beings doing our best.
Photo and caption by @maisiesghost

node.text:
in my ongoing journey to improve myself as a person, one of the biggest things I had to unlearn from my childhood was the idea that I was "not like other girls", and that somehow made me better than them. I prided myself in being different than them, but what was really happening was that I was alienating myself from people with whom I actually shared a lot in common. I like video games, but I later found that I like shopping, too! it wasn't until around the time I finished high school and entered college that I realized I just never *let* myself like these things because I so badly wanted to be "not like other girls". so, other girls, let's support one another - because we're in this together. ❤
Art & caption by @juliehang.art

node.text:
When you struggle with anxiety, there are constant ‘what ifs...’ There are constant worrying thoughts about all of the awful things that could happen. And so flipping that around, and asking ourselves ‘what are the good things that could happen?’ is so important to do. Anxiety will always focus on the bad things, the worst-case scenarios. But this is not an accurate representation of reality. Most of the time those awful scenarios you have thought of will not happen. In order to challenge anxiety, we must challenge our thoughts. Ask yourself what is the best thing that could happen? What if this goes to plan? What if I actually prove anxiety wrong? Because when you do challenge anxiety, you prove to yourself that things are nowhere near as bad as you imagined. You prove to yourself that you are strong, capable, and able to deal with your anxiety❤️
Photo & caption by @worrywellbeing
